cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|marion brings up an interesting point about 3rd hand openings. Let me give you some historical perspective. My style is to open all rule of 20 hands in all seats, and not open light. The reason being, if you open light, then pard will not know how high to compete. Again, that is just the style I prefer. Others may prefer opening light.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But let me explain why light openings in 3rd and 4th seat were originally invented. In the 50s thru early 80s, most experts preferred a style of bidding where openers in first and second seat were strong. They would usually not open with less than a good 14 or so. Therefore, it was necessary for 3rd and 4th to open light, because otherwise game could be missed. I used to love that style, because I always liked to play light openers, and in my younger days, I would preempt the heck out of the pros and leave them shaking their heads. |
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, since then, everyone figured out that aggressive bidding pays off and everyone opens lighter these days. Thus, the need for opening light in 3rd and 4th seat is no longer necessary, as you will not miss game if neither partner nor you have an opening hand. My feeling is you should only open rule of 20 hands in all seats. That way partner can count on you for certain values. Otherwise your hand is too undefined. That is just my opinion. Other experts disagree.|
