Here is a brief explanation of Bergen Raises by Howard.
^-
^B@2Bergen Raises are used by responder after partner opens one of a major and responder has 4 cards in the opener's @E@3suit. Reverse Bergen, which I recommend, works as follows. Responder must have exactly 4 card support. 
With 5-6 points, responder jumps to 3 of the major, 
with 7 to a bad 9 responder bids 3 diamonds (known as a "constructive raise"), 
with a good 9 to 11 responder bids 3 clubs (known as a "limit raise"), 
and with 12 or more responder bids 2N (the usual Jacoby 2N raise played by many partnerships.)

One of the important advantages of Bergen Raises is the preemptive jump raise (with 5-6 points). Modern competitive bidding theory says it is safe to compete to the 3 level with a 9 card fit, and Bergen Raises allow you to do this in a way that preempts the opponents.

If the intervening opponent bids, Bergen Raises no longer apply. I suggest you play the following methods over interference. If the opponent bids a suit, 
a cue bid shows a limit raise (9-11) with 4 card support. 
A jump raise shows less than a limit raise (5-8) with 4 card support. 
Over a takeout double, 2N shows a limit raise or better with 4 card support (this convention is known as Jordan 2N). And a jump raise still shows less than a limit raise (5-8) with 4 card support.

Some people play regular Bergen rather than Reverse Bergen. The idea is basically the same, only the meaning of the 3 club and 3 diamond bids are reverse, 3 clubs showing 7 to a bad 9 and 3 diamonds showing a good 9 to 11. The reason I prefer Reverse Bergen is that you want to explore for game more often over a limit raise than a constructive raise, and Reverse Bergen gives your partnership more room to explore. However, if your partner insists on playing regular Bergen, most of the value of Bergen Raises still applies.

And finally, yes, I still play Bergen by a passed hand. I cannot think of any good reason why Bergen would be off with a passed hand.|
