Bergen's new book finally gave me logical definitions for both.  There are no reasons for me to memorize numbers and @E@3conditions which easily can be forgotten. Therefore, I am adopting Bergen's treatment of Jacoby 2NT and Splinter Bids. I am in good company because Howard plays both conventions the same way. Let me quote the explanation of the Jacoby 2NT and Splinter Bids from Bergen's book.|CS|4|at|

^-{          Jacoby 2NT by Marty Bergen          }
^-|at|
^b@2- Partner opens 1@H/1@s
- You are unpassed hand and the RHO passes
- You have 13+ "dummy points" with no upper limits. You could have fewer than 13 "HCP".  Please note the two |AT|
^B   differen yard stick of dummy points and HCP. 
- You have 4+ card support, you may have a strong side suit. And, with 17+ dummy points you bid 2NT even with a |AT|^B
   singleton. Therefore, with 13-16 dummy points and a singleton you bid splinter.|AT|

^-{          Splinter Bids by Marty Bergen          }
^-|AT|
^b@2Splinter Bids in Bergen's book is long and has sections for different skill levels. Here you will find the basics.
- Partner opens 1@H/1@S
- You have 4-card support
- You have a singleton (it could be an honor) or void. 
- You have 13-16 dummy points. Remember, with 17+ dummy points you bid Jacoby 2NT regardless even if you |AT|^B
   have a singleton.

^B@2As you note the explanations for both conventions and the rebids are simple and logical. I have to memorize only the 17+ and the rest are natural. For a comprehensive study of the topic and how to properly evaluate the hands please review "Better Slam Bidding with Bergen" by Marty Bergen. Further, I hope that they are part of Howards lessons in January 2009. Next, are quizzes on Bergen raises. You are sitting South, partner opens 1@H/!@S. Please note that there may be more than one good answer. It is easier to fly to the moon than find agreement between two bridge experts on a simple issue.|
